07178nam a22010815i 9781501511257DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212021gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021935983  a97815015112577 a10.1515/97815015112572doi  a(DE-B1597)502003  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a417.2200aNew Perspectives on Mixed Languages :bFrom Core to Fringe /ced. by Maria Mazzoli, Eeva Sippola. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2021] 4c©2021  a1 online resource (VIII, 408 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aLanguage Contact and Bilingualism [LCB] ;v1800tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMixed languages: From core to fringe -- tNoun-Verb mixed languages: Similarities and differences -- tAdvances in mixed language phonology: An overview of three case studies -- tHow sentence processing sheds light on mixed language creation -- tMichif mixed verbs: Typologically unusual word-internal mixing -- tVO vs. OV: What conditions word order variation in Media Lengua? -- tLinguistic manipulations in Kallawaya -- tSocial identity and the formation and development of Barranquenho -- tIlokano-Spanish: Borrowing, code-switching or a mixed language? -- tJopara as a case of a variable mixed language -- tPronominal usage in Cité Duits, a Dutch-German-Limburgish contact variety -- tWutun as a mixed language -- tRepertoire management and the performative origin of Mixed Languages -- tSubject Index -- tLanguage Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA growing number of language varieties with diverse backgrounds and structural typologies have been identified as mixed. However, the debate on the status of many varieties and even on the existence of the category of “mixed languages” continues still today.This volume examines the current state of the theoretical and empirical debate on mixed languages and presents new advances from a diverse set of mixed language varieties. These cover well-known mixed languages, such as Media Lengua, Michif, Gurindji Kriol, and Kallawaya, and varieties whose classification is still debated, such as Reo Rapa, Kumzari, Jopará, and Wutun. The contributions deal with different aspects of mixed languages, including descriptive approaches to their current status and origins, theoretical discussions on the language contact processes in them, and analysis of different types of language mixing practices.This book contributes to the current debate on the existence of the mixed language category, shedding more light onto this fascinating group of languages and the contact processes that shape them.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 4aMischsprache. 4aSprachkontakt. 4aZweisprachigkeit. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aBilingualism.  aContact Languages.  aHistorical Linguistics.  aLanguage Contact.  aSociolinguistics.1 aAdamou, Evangelia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAmaral, Patrícia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBakker, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aClancy Clements, J, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeMontigny, Verna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeibel, Isabel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGarrett, Jordan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHannß, Katja, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHerring Dudek, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMatras, Yaron, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabul